<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-034-622  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 034 622.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Jan 8 1990 v36 n1791 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>East Bloc seen playing catch-up, needing range of products.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collier, Andrew.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The wave of democracy sweeping across Eastern Europe has Westernelectronics firms envisioning burgeoning new markets.andP;  Regulationsimposed by the Coordinating Committee for Multilateral ExportControls (CoCom) in response to security concerns of the Westlimit the opportunities currently open to Western companies andrelaxation of those restraints has been called for.andP;  In the areaof telecommunications, however, opportunities already exist andare expected to grow with the easing of current restrictions.andO;Spending on telecommunications equipment by the Soviet Union andEastern Bloc nations is expected to reach $15.8 billion in 1990and to continue to grow, reaching $24.2 billion in 1995.andP;  Otherareas of opportunity include data entry systems.andP;  Methods ofpayment pose special problems because of the non-convertability ofEastern Bloc currencies.andP;  Alternatives include governmentfinancing and payment in kind.andP;  Among the goods that have beenoffered in exchange for Western goods are furniture, wine andvodka.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United StatesSoviet UnionEuropeCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>